`/home/bwang56/my-SIMBA/Control_Server/server.c`, lines 179-183:

```c
//motor_set_speed(MOTOR_REAR_RIGHT_WHEEL, speed);
//motor_set_speed(MOTOR_REAR_LEFT_WHEEL, speed);
//rover_forward(128);
//rover_reverse(128);
//printf("calibrating...\n");
// wait for calibration to finish
//while (rover_is_calibrated() == false){}
//printf("done.\n");
```

All those lines have `//` in front of them, so none of them execute. The calibration busy-wait is line 182.

No, `rover_forward` would not block. Looking at the implementation:

```c
void rover_forward(int speed) {
  motor_set_speed(FRW, -speed);
  motor_set_speed(MRW, -speed);
  motor_set_speed(RRW, -speed);
  motor_set_speed(FLW, speed);
  motor_set_speed(MLW, speed);
  motor_set_speed(RLW, speed);
}
```

It just sets speed limits on the servo PID structs and returns. The actual motor movement happens asynchronously in the ISR. So uncommenting `//rover_forward(128);` would start the wheels spinning and immediately fall through to `server_init`.

The ISR is set up in `isr_init()` to fire every 1ms via `SIGALRM`:

```c
timer.it_interval.tv_usec = ISR_DELAY; // 1000 usec = 1ms
setitimer(ITIMER_REAL, &timer, NULL);
```

Every 1ms the OS interrupts the main thread and runs `isr()`:

```c
void isr(int signum) {
  *(watchdog_flag) = *(watchdog_flag) ? 0 : 1;  // pet the watchdog
  for (unsigned i = 0; i < isr_num_functions; i++) {
    isr_functions[i]();  // calls rover_isr()
  }
}
```

Which calls `rover_isr()`:

```c
void rover_isr() {
  if (rover_is_calibrated() == false)
    rover_calibrate();
  rover_update_steering();
  for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++)
    Servo_update(&servos[i]);  // <-- this is what actually drives the motors
}
```

So the flow is:
1. `rover_forward(speed)` sets PID output limits on the servo structs (just a struct write, returns instantly)
2. Every 1ms, the SIGALRM fires and `Servo_update()` runs the PID loop for each motor — reading encoder counts, computing the PID output, and writing PWM values to the FPGA hardware registers

The main thread never touches the motors directly after calling `rover_forward`. The ISR is doing all the real work in the background at 1kHz.

